(44, 16, 26, 19, 146, 7, 7, NULL, 'Loosening of Prisoners', 'Both passages emphasize the act of loosening prisoners. Acts 16:26 describes a miraculous event where prisoners are freed, while Psalms 146:7 speaks of the Lord''s role in loosening the prisoners, highlighting a theme of divine deliverance.', 'theme', 0.356, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 26, 40, 28, 2, 2, 'great earthquake', 'Earthquake as a Divine Sign', 'Both passages emphasize a great earthquake occurring at pivotal moments. In Acts, the earthquake leads to the liberation of prisoners, while in Matthew, it accompanies the resurrection event, signifying divine intervention.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 26, 19, 102, 20, 20, NULL, 'Prison and Liberation Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the liberation of prisoners. Acts 16:26 describes an earthquake that frees prisoners, while Psalms 102:20 speaks of loosing those appointed to death.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 26, 23, 42, 7, 7, NULL, 'Prison and Liberation Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of liberation from prison. Acts 16:26 describes a miraculous release from physical imprisonment, while Isaiah 42:7 speaks of bringing prisoners out of darkness, suggesting a broader spiritual liberation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 26, 23, 61, 1, 1, NULL, 'Connection of Liberation Themes', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of liberation, with Acts 16:26 describing a physical release from prison and Isaiah 61:1 proclaiming liberty to the captives. This connection highlights the transformative power of divine intervention in freeing those who are bound.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 27, 44, 12, 19, 19, NULL, 'Prison Keeper''s Fate', 'This connection highlights the fate of prison keepers in both passages. In Acts 16:27, the keeper''s instinct to kill himself parallels the punishment of the keepers in Acts 12:19, emphasizing the severe consequences faced by those responsible for prisoners.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 27, 7, 9, 54, 54, NULL, 'Suicidal Actions in Crisis', 'This connection highlights the theme of desperation leading to suicidal thoughts in both passages. In Acts, the prison keeper contemplates death upon believing the prisoners have escaped, while in Judges, Abimelech requests his armor-bearer to kill him to avoid disgrace.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 27, 9, 31, 4, 5, 'would have killed himself', 'Suicide in Despair', 'This connection highlights the theme of despair leading to suicide in both passages. The prison keeper, like Saul, contemplates death when faced with hopelessness and fear of consequences.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 27, 10, 17, 23, 23, 'would have killed himself', 'Suicidal Actions in Crisis', 'This connection highlights the theme of despair leading to suicide in moments of crisis. Both passages depict individuals who, faced with overwhelming circumstances, choose to end their lives rather than confront the consequences of their situations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 27, 11, 16, 18, 18, NULL, 'Suicidal Despair in Crisis', 'This connection highlights the theme of despair in moments of crisis. Both the prison keeper and Zimri face imminent death, leading them to consider suicide as a response to their dire situations.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 27, 40, 27, 5, 5, 'would have killed himself', 'Suicidal Despair in Context', 'This connection highlights the theme of despair leading to suicide in both passages. The prison keeper, fearing the consequences of lost prisoners, and Judas, overwhelmed by guilt, both resort to taking their own lives.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 27, 44, 16, 23, 24, NULL, 'Prison and Despair Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the dire situation of the jailor. In Acts 16:23-24, he is tasked with keeping the prisoners safely, and in Acts 16:27, he faces despair upon discovering the open prison doors.', 'theme', 0.307, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 28, 52, 5, 15, 15, 'Do thyself no harm', 'Response to Harm and Goodness', 'This connection highlights the theme of responding to harm with goodness. In Acts, Paul prevents harm by urging calm, while in 1 Thessalonians, believers are instructed to avoid rendering evil for evil. Both passages emphasize the importance of maintaining good conduct in the face of adversity.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 28, 42, 6, 27, 28, 'Do thyself no harm', 'Love and Protection in Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of responding to harm with compassion. In Acts, Paul prevents self-harm, while in Luke, believers are instructed to love and bless those who harm them.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 28, 42, 23, 34, 34, NULL, 'Expressions of Mercy in Crisis', 'This connection highlights the theme of mercy in dire situations. Both Paul and Jesus express concern for others'' well-being, emphasizing forgiveness and preservation of life.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 28, 21, 7, 17, 17, 'Do thyself no harm', 'Connection of Life Preservation', 'This connection highlights the theme of self-preservation in both passages. Paul’s plea to avoid harm resonates with the warning against foolishness that leads to premature death in Ecclesiastes.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 28, 40, 5, 44, 44, 'Do thyself no harm', 'Response to Adversity', 'This connection highlights the theme of responding to harm with compassion. In Acts, Paul urges the jailer not to harm himself, paralleling the call in Matthew to love and do good to those who may cause harm.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 28, 2, 20, 13, 13, 'Do thyself no harm', 'Value of Life and Preservation', 'This connection highlights the theme of preserving life. In Acts 16:28, Paul urges the jailer not to harm himself, reflecting the commandment in Exodus 20:13 to not kill.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 28, 3, 19, 18, 18, 'Do thyself no harm', 'Love and Preservation of Life', 'This connection highlights the theme of valuing life and the call to love others. In Acts, Paul urges the jailer not to harm himself, reflecting the command in Leviticus to love one''s neighbor as oneself.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 16, 29, 66, 3, 9, 9, 'fell down before Paul and Silas', 'Worship and Humility', 'This connection highlights the act of falling down in reverence, as seen in both passages. The trembling before Paul and Silas in Acts parallels the worship before the feet in Revelation, emphasizing humility and recognition of divine authority.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
